	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>What is Payola Diplomacy anyway?</b><br>
	Basically, Payola Diplomacy is a standard game of Diplomacy (on any
	game map, etc.) in which each player has a treasury of "silver pieces"
	that he uses to make "offers" to each of the various pieces on the
	board (other players' units but also his own).  Each player must pay
	his own armies and fleets enough to get them to follow the orders he
	wishes them to follow, or risk them doing the bidding of another player.
	The units' only motives in deciding which order to follow, from among
	those that the players suggest, are purely financial.  Think of it as
	having all of the armies and fleets on the game-board led by 
	money-hungry generals and admirals, whose loyalty to
	their various political leaders goes out the window the minute
	a better monetary offer comes along.

<P><b>Okay, but what is the game of Diplomacy?</b><br>
	If you asked this question, you have my sympathy that you managed to
	live long enough to form intelligent questions without becoming
	acquainted with -- nay, addicted to -- Diplomacy.  I won't answer the
	question here, but will instead refer you to the Internet home page
	of the Diplomacy hobby, <a href=<POUCH>>The
	Diplomatic Pouch</a>, where you can find the answer you seek.
	The Pouch is chock full of more information on The Game
	than you can digest in one sitting -- one place to start is
	<a href=<URL>/Welcome.html>The Pouch's "Welcome"
	page</a>, where I wrote a quickie overview of Diplomacy itself.
	<i>(Head for The Pouch now, because
	the rest of these questions are answered assuming that you are familiar
	with Diplomacy, and most Payola players cut their teeth on the standard
	game first before trying to deal with the possibility that their
	own units won't obey orders.)</i>
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

