		<tr><td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" class="grey" align=center><a name="2"></a><b>Income and Expenses</b></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		</table>	
	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>Okay, so I am playing Diplomacy with a treasury full
of Monopoly money.  How much do I have and how and when do I get more?</b><br>
	There are a number of answers to this question, because there are
	different "flavors" of Payola.  What I describe here is the income
	scheme for the standard game of Payola.  Players start the game with
	a treasury based on the number of supply centers owned by each power.
	Then, players receive "tax" income, an amount again
	based on the number of supply centers held by that player,
	once per game-year -- immediately after the Fall phases of the game.
	The amount of "tax" income is a simple decreasing sequence.  You receive
	17 silver pieces if you own one supply center, 17+16 if you own two,
	17+16+15 if you own three, etc.
	<P>
	As I mentioned, that is only one of a number of recognized income
	models.  Others include
	<ul>
	<li>the "flat tax" model, in which all
		supply centers are worth the same amount of annual income,
	<li>the "economic" model, in which each individual supply center
		is separately valued, and is worth a specific, variable, annual income,
		and
	<li>the "zero sum" model, in which all supply centers are worth
		ten silver pieces awarded once only, funds are transferred from one
		player to another when a supply center changes hands,
		and all of the money paid (as accepted offers made to each player's
		units during the game-year) is added to that player's
		treasury at the end of the year (in standard Payola, money spent on
		accepted offers is gone forever; spent by the generals and admirals
		at the officers' club).
	</ul>

<P><b>Do I need to spend all my money every phase or
game-year?  Is the money one of those "use it or lose it" things?
</b><br>
	No, you most certainly do <i>not</i> need to spend all your money.
	In fact, since you only receive money at the end of each year, you
	would be very foolish to spend all your money in the Spring turn of
	a year!  You should save as much as you think you can.  Someday, you
	will hopefully have a big treasure chest full of loot that you can
	use to pay an enemy army to simply step aside and let you walk into
	the supply center that gives you a solo victory.

<P><b>Before I ask you how to make an offer to a unit, is that
the only thing I can do with my money?</b><br>
	No, you can transfer some or all of it to any other player.  You can do 
	this at any time, and the transfer is instantaneous.  Players take
	advantage of this capability to make amends for little "accidental" moves
	their units make, and to signal peaceful intentions in games without
	press.
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

