		<tr><td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" class="grey" align=center><a name="3"></a><b>Offer Syntax</b></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		</table>	
	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>Okay, I'm ready to learn how to make offers to the pieces now.
How do I do it?  What are the different types of offers I can make to
the pieces on the board?</b><br>
	In Payola, there are five different types of offers.  Here are examples
	of each, with an explanation:
	<ul>
	<p><li><b>Direct Offer.</b>  The offer below is a promise to pay four
		"silver pieces" if the army in Paris attempts to move to Burgundy.
		<dd><tt>4 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd><br>
		Direct offers are the most common of the offer types.  Many players
		use only direct offers throughout a game.
	<p><li><b>Negative Offer.</b>  The offer below is a promise to pay four
		"silver pieces" if the army in Paris does <u>not</u> attempt to
		move to Burgundy.
		<dd><tt>4 ! A PAR - BUR</tt></dd><br>
		As long as the army in Paris does anything <i>other than</i> try
		to move to Burgundy, the treasury of the player issuing this offer
		will be debited four silver pieces.
	<p><li><b>Move Offer.</b> The offer below is a promise to pay four "silver
		pieces if the army in Paris tries to move either to Burgundy or
		to anywhere else.
		<dd><tt>4 &gt; A PAR - BUR</tt></dd><br>
		Yes, that's right.  If the army in Paris attempts to move
		<i>any</i>where (not just to Burgundy, but to any space adjacent
		to Paris), it will cost the player four silver pieces from his
		treasury.
	<p><li><b>Hold Offer.</b> The offer below is a promise to pay four
		"silver pieces" if the army in Paris either does not attempt
		to move at all, or attempts to move only to Burgundy.
		<dd><tt>4 @ A PAR - BUR</tt></dd><br>
		Because the order I included in the above example is a <i>move</i>
		order, the meaning of the example offer may seem a bit confusing, so
		let me explain.  The at-sign
		in the offer does indeed mean that the amount offered will be paid if
		the unit does <i>not</i> move.  That is, four silver pieces will be
		paid if the unit issues
		a <tt>HOLD</tt> or <tt>SUPPORT</tt> order.  But four silver pieces
		are <i>also</i> offered for any order or orders mentioned in the
		offer, whether it is a stationary order or not, so
		an attempt to move from to Burgundy would also cost the player those
		four silver pieces.
	<p><li><b>Gift Offer.</b>  The offer below is a promise to pay four
		"silver pieces" <i>no matter what order is issued</i> to the army
		in Paris.
		<dd><tt>4 &amp; A PAR - BUR</tt></dd><br>
		Yes, you read that right.  A gift offer is a simple drain on your
		treasury.  Whatever the army in Paris does, it's going to cost you
		four silver pieces if you made this offer.  You probably are
		not surprised to hear that the gift offer is
		very rarely used in practice.
	</ul>

<P><b>Can I make more than one offer to a single unit?</b><br>
	Yes, you can.  Here are some examples:
	<ul>
	<p><li>Let's say that you didn't care whether
	the army in Paris moved to Burgundy or Gascony but that you're willing
	to pay four silver pieces if it attempts either one of these moves.
	You could write this as follows:
	<dd><tt>4 : A PAR - BUR<br>4 : A PAR - GAS</tt></dd><br>
	Note that because the move to Burgundy is listed first, the unit will
	prefer that over the move to Gascony if it comes down to a choice between
	these two orders.
	<P><li>You can also use a shorthand syntax to express this same set of two
	offers as a single offer:
	<dd><tt>4 : A PAR - BUR | - GAS</tt></dd><br>
	The vertical bar comes in handy.  The only thing to remember is that
	you do <i>not</i> list the unit's type (<tt>A</tt>) and its
	current location (<tt>PAR</tt>) more than once in the offer.
	<p><li>
	Multiple offers to the same unit have other more varied uses.
	For example, let's say you wished to 
	would pay four silver pieces for Paris to move anywhere (probably because
	you want
	to make sure that the army would be unsupportable on the upcoming turn),
	but that for some reason 
	you are willing to pay two <i>extra</i> silver pieces if it moves
	to Burgundy as opposed to anywhere else.  You could express this with
	these offers:
	<dd><tt>4 &gt; A PAR - BUR<br>2 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd><br>
	</ul>

<P><b>How do I ask a unit <i><u>not</u></i> to do more than one thing?</b><br>
	You may have realized that the following offers:
	<ul><dd><tt>4 ! A PAR - BUR<br>4 ! A PAR - GAS</tt></dd></ul>
	(which say "four silver pieces if you don't move to Burgundy" and
	"four silver pieces if you don't move to Gascony," respectively) will end up
	costing the player four silver pieces if the unit actually <i>does</i>
	attempt to move to Burgundy or Gascony, and <i>eight</i> silver
	pieces if it is issued any <i>other</i> order.
	<P>
	What the player probably wished to say was "four if you don't move
	to Burgundy <i><u>and</u></i> you don't move to Gascony."  This offer
	<i>must</i> be expressed using the vertical bar, like this:
	<ul><dd><tt>4 ! A PAR - BUR | - GAS</tt></dd></ul>
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

