		<tr><td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" class="grey" align=center><a name="4"></a><b>Offer Interactions (Including the coastal support question</b></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		</table>	
	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>Can I pay a foreign unit to support me in my attempt
to dislodge another unit owned by that same foreign power?</b><br>
Yes and no.  Yes, you can pay the unit, and yes, it will issue the support
(and take your money).  However, remember this: units follow <i>all</i> the
standard
Diplomacy rules, no matter who pays them.  So the support you bought will
be invalid when it comes to aiding in the dislodge.  For example, if
the following orders are bought and paid for:
<center><table><tr><td>
<tt>English F MAO-Por
<br>&nbsp;French A Por H
<br>&nbsp;French A Spa S F MAO-Por</tt>
</table></center>
the French unit in Portugal will remain and the English attack will fail,
because -- by rule -- a French support cannot cause a French dislodgement.

<P><b>Is my money for a particular order combined with
money that other players offer for that same order?</b><br>
	Yes, it is.  If you offer Paris some of your silver pieces to move to
	Burgundy, and if any one (or more) of the other players offer Paris some
	of their own silver pieces for the same order, the army will indeed
	consider the multiple offers
	as if they were a single, consolidated offer to pay it the sum total of
	all the monies offered by the separate players.

<P><b>What if I offer money for a fleet in Constantinople
to move to the east coast of Bulgaria, and someone else offers it money
to move to the <i>south</i> coast.  Are our offers combined?</b><br>
	No.  Those are two separate orders.

<P><b>What if I wish to <i>support</i> a Constantinople
fleet's move to a particular coast of Bulgaria?  The Website is not
letting me enter the offer.  How do I do it?</b><br>
	You cannot.  You may offer support for the fleet to move to Bulgaria,
	but not to a specific coast of Bulgaria.  This is the proper implementation
	of the Diplomacy rules &mdash; support is directed to a <i>space</i>, not to
	a specific <i>coast</i>.
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

		<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" class="grey" align=center><a name="5"></a><b>High-Bid Ties and the Acceptance List</b></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		</table>	
	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>What about ties?  If my offer is for the same amount as
another player's offer, what will the unit do?</b><br>
	If two (or more) orders would pay a unit the same amount of money, one of
	these will be preferred over the other by virtue of the tie-breakers.
	The mechanism that implements the tie-breaker is the "acceptance list."
	Every player has an "acceptance list" on file, and it applies to all
	offers made to his own units.  An acceptance list of <tt>EFRTIGA</tt>
	means that, among tied offers, any with money offered by England (listed
	first in the "acceptance list") are preferred over those without.
	Players can update their acceptance lists at any time during the game.
	<i>(I will not go further here in explaining the use of the "acceptance
	list" to break ties -- for more information, see Section 4 of
	<a href=<POUCH>/Zine/W1995A/Payola>the rules to
	Payola</a>.)</i>

<P><b>Does the acceptance list really matter?  Do I really
need to keep an eye on it and change it every season?</b><br>
	Well, you can check the data for all the completed Payola games (offer
	histories become public knowledge at the end of the game) to find instances
	where the acceptance list came into play to break a tie, but the fact is
	that, in practice, these are few and far between.  As long as you have
	your own power at the front of your acceptance list, you can probably
	feel pretty safe.  Many players play an entire game without changing their
	acceptance list once.  However, don't take this as a recommendation.
	A player who meticulously updates his acceptance list to reflect the
	changing attitudes of other players toward him will have
	an advantage over those who don't, if ever the occasion arrives.
	<P>
	The reason why the acceptance list is not of paramount importance is
	that
	if you have a unit that is being offered money to do something you don't
	want it to do, it probably doesn't matter to you whether the power
	doing the offering is someone you thought was your friend or someone
	you knew was your enemy.  Therefore, when you have a unit deciding
	between two tied
	orders -- neither of which includes money (or even a zero silver piece
	bid) offered by you -- does it really
	matter which of them it accepts?  Yes, it will accept the one more
	preferred by the power you listed earlier in your acceptance list, but
	can you really be sure that this order is the one truly more preferred
	by you??  Nope.
	<P>
	There could be cases, however, when you just don't have the money to
	do what you want so you leave ordering your units in the hands of
	a (hopefully) loyal ally -- not loyal enough to transfer you some money
	to handle the problem yourself, though, apparently.  Assuming he
	doesn't cross you up, you might
	want to be sure to list him high in your acceptance list to avoid the
	risk of his being one silver
	piece short on a crucial bid, which then goes to a tie-break that is
	decided against him.  However, since you can issue zero AgP offers to your
	own units -- and assuming you list yourself at the front of your acceptance
	list (you'd rarely not do so!) -- you can tip the balance in favor of
	your ally's planned bids to your units, even if he is listed dead-last
	in your acceptance list.  In fact, you may want to do just that -- list
	him last, so that if he does cross you up, his bids won't match your
	zero silver piece "helper bids," and his bids will run the risk of losing
	a tie-break to an offer made by another power.  (Of course, if this happens,
	it just means that your
	unit is controlled by someone you considered to be even more against you
	than your would-be treacherous "friend," and that you've allowed that
	"friend" to save the money he was about to stab you with so that he can
	use it to try to do so again next season!  If he honestly tells you
	how much he spent, though,
	in attempting the offer -- lying to you only about what the order was
	that he listed in his offer -- you can tell from your account statement
	that he lost a tie-break, and his treachery will be exposed to you.)
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

		<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" class="grey" align=center><a name="6"></a><b>Overexpenditure and Money Management</b></td></tr>
		<tr><td bgcolor="#666666" height=1 class="border"><img src="<URL>/images/spacer.gif" height=1></td></tr>
		</table>	
	<table border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--ANSWERS BEGINS HERE-->
		<b>Can I make offers whose amounts total to
more money than I have in my treasury?</b><br>
	Yes, you can.  But of course, if you do, and if enough of your offers
	turn out to be accepted, you won't be able to afford them all.  If this
	happens, your offers are automatically devalued and the units try again
	to see if they can meet your demands without leaving you bankrupt.
	This all happens behind the scenes, simultaneously for all such
	"overgenerous" players, and is done as follows:
	<ul>
	<li>
	First, <i>every single one</i> of your offers is <i>reduced</i> by a single
	"silver piece."  That is,
	<dd><tt>4 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd><br>
	becomes
	<dd><tt>3 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd>
	<li>Then <i>all the units on the board</i> start all over again deciding
	what order they will issue.  What you could have bought for four silver
	pieces, you might not be able to buy for three.
	<li>If, after the units
	decide on their orders <i>again</i>, you are <i>still</i> promising them
	more than you could pay, your offers are <i>all</i> reduced by
	<i>another</i> "silver piece."  This continues until you can afford to
	pay all the units that accept your offers.
	</ul>

<P><b>Okay, I understand.  If I overcommit, all of my offers
will be reduced one silver piece, then re-offered to the various units,
with this reduction and re-offering repeated if necessary.
What if there are some of my offers that I care less about than others?
Can I somehow have these less important offers reduce at a faster rate, in
order to give the others a better chance to be accepted?</b><br>
    Yes, you can.  The way you do this is by splitting any offer that
	you wish to have reduce quicker than by one silver piece into
	multiple parts.  For example, if you
	wish to offer an eight silver piece offer for Paris to move to Burgundy,
    but you wish it to reduce by two silver pieces rather
    than by one, you would split the offer into two parts:
    <ul><dd><tt>4 : A PAR - BUR<dd>4 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd></ul>
    There is a convenient shorthand for this as well:
    <ul><dd><tt>2 * 4 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd></ul>
<!--
Planning how quickly your bids would reduce can be
a good way to implement different campaign possibilities. With some orders
decreasing faster than others, if it turns out you can't afford your
preferred campaign, an alternate plan (its offers reducing slower) could
become the more attractive to the units to which you're making offers.
<P>
For (an oversimplified) example, if your treasury contains twenty silver
pieces and you wish to stab your ally Germany, but only if you can walk into
<i>both</i> of the centers he's left open to you (otherwise, you will follow
the plan you have negotiated with him), your offer sheet might look like this:
    <ul><dd><tt>
	10 : A BUR - MUN<br>
	10 : A BUR - MUN<br>
	10 : A RUH - KIE<br>
	10 : A RUH - KIE<br>
	20 : A RUH S A BEL<br>
	20 : A BUR S A BEL
	</tt></dd></ul>
With this offer sheet, the orders to take Munich and Kiel are preferred
to those that offer support to Belgium.  However, the highest
price you would pay for both these "campaigns" is the same (40 silver
pieces).  If you can afford
-->
<P><b>
That sounds neat, but it seems like I can only do this kind of planned
reduction if
I structure my bids to make <i>sure</i> to overspend my treasury.  Is there
any way I can set some of my money aside -- maybe it's only Spring and I
need to make sure to have money for the Fall phase --
and still have all the same bribing flexibility?
</b><br>
	Yes, there is.  You can specify with your offers that -- no
	matter what happens -- you wish to be left with a specific amount of money
	after the units are given their orders.  This is done by including a
	"savings request" with your offers.  For example, to guarantee that
	your treasury will contain at least twenty-five "silver pieces" after
	the current turn, include the line:
	<ul><dd><tt>25 $</tt></dd></ul>
	with your offers.
	(Note that if you include more than one savings request in an
	offer sheet, they will be totaled to create a single request.)
	The savings request simply means that if enough of your offers would be
	accepted to leave you with fewer silver pieces than requested,
	your offers are subjected to the one-silver-piece-at-a-time
	devaluation described above, until all the acceptable offers
	are also payable without violating your savings request.
	<P><b>
Is there any other money-management tool
or technique I can take advantage of?</b><br>
	Yes, there is one more; the "offer plateau."  You can give
	any of your offers a "plateau" amount, which comes into play
	if your offers need to be reduced.  Each offer, as discussed above,
	is reduced in value by a single silver piece; <i>however</i>, an offer
	is never reduced lower than its "plateau" amount unless and
	until <i>every one</i> of the
	player's offers reaches its plateau.  Here is an example:
	<ul><dd><tt>8#4 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd></ul>
	This offer is for eight silver pieces, but directs that it should not
	be reduced (if reduction is necessary) to any amount lower than four
	silver pieces.  The only way this offer could be reduced to offer an
	amount of three "silver pieces" or fewer is if all of the player's
	offers are reduced to their plateau amounts
	but the player is still "overextended" -- if this happens, this offer
	and all of this player's other offers will then "forget their plateau"
	and continue to be reduced, down to zero if need be.
	<P>
	Any offer that does not include a pound-sign character to indicate a
	plateau has a plateau amount of zero.  Additionally, a useful shorthand
	is recognized:  the offer
	<ul><dd><tt>8# : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd></ul>
	is an eight "silver piece" offer that should not be reduced at all.
	That is, it is equivalent to:
	<ul><dd><tt>8#8 : A PAR - BUR</tt></dd></ul>
		<!--ANSWERS ENDS HERE-->
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>

